__NOTOC__
'''Tenno Jinja''' (天王神社、天王社) is a Shinto shrine dedicated to {{ill|Gozu Tennō|ja|牛頭天王|1=Gozu Tennō|1=Gozu Tennō|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and {{ill|Susanoo|ja|スサノオ|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, central deities in {{ill|Gion Faith|ja|祇園信仰|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. This name is especially used for shrines in the lineage of {{ill|Tsushima Shrine|ja|津島神社|qq=draft|qq=draft}} in {{ill|Tsushima City, Aichi Prefecture|ja|津島市|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. Other shrines based on Gion Faith include {{ill|Yasaka Shrine (disambiguation)|ja|八坂神社 (曖昧さ回避)|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Gion Shrine|ja|祇園神社|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Hiromine Shrine (disambiguation)|ja|広峯神社 (曖昧さ回避)|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Yakumo Shrine|ja|八雲神社|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Suga Shrine|ja|須賀神社|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, and {{ill|Susanoo Shrine|ja|素盞嗚神社|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, whose usage varies by era and source.

Currently, only a few shrines still worship Gozu Tennō directly. Most shrines now enshrine {{ill|Susanoo|ja|スサノオ|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, who was syncretized with Gozu Tennō under {{ill|Shinbutsu-shūgō|ja|神仏習合|1=Shinbutsu-shūgō|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. During the {{ill|Shinbutsu bunri|ja|神仏分離|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (separation of Shinto and Buddhism) in the {{ill|Meiji era|ja|明治|1=Meiji era|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, some shrines reverted to deities listed in ancient records other than Susanoo.

Since the Meiji period, many shrines have been merged with others or renamed to align with the Tsushima Gozu Tennōsha, such as renaming to {{ill|Tsushima Shrine|ja|津島神社|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. As a result of Shinbutsu bunri and shrine mergers, some shrines now enshrine deities other than Gozu Tennō or interpret Gozu Tennō as a deity distinct from Susanoo. In some regions, the influence of these shrines can still be seen in place names incorporating "Tenno."

