==Merged second translation==
__NOTOC__
'''Tennō Shrine''' (天王神社) and '''Tennō-sha''' (天王社) are Shinto shrines of the {{ill|Gion Faith|ja|祇園信仰|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Gion Faith|qq=}} tradition that enshrine {{ill|Gozu Tennō|ja|牛頭天王|1=Gozu Tennō|1=Gozu Tennō|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Gozu Tennō|13=User:Immanuelle/Gozu Tennō|qq=}} and {{ill|Susanoo|1=Susanoo-no-Mikoto|ja|スサノオ|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Susanoo|13=User:Immanuelle/Susanoo-no-Mikoto|qq=}}.

It is observed that this name is used in shrines belonging to the lineage of {{ill|Tsushima Shrine|ja|津島神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tsushima Shrine|qq=}} (Tsushima City, Aichi Prefecture). Other shrine names based on the Gion faith include {{ill|Yasaka Shrine (disambiguation)|ja|八坂神社 (曖昧さ回避)|lt=Yasaka Shrine|lt_ja=八坂神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yasaka Shrine (disambiguation)|qq=}} (also known as {{ill|Yaei Shrine|ja|弥栄神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yaei Shrine|qq=}}), {{ill|Gion Shrine|ja|祇園神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Gion Shrine|qq=}}, {{ill|Hiromine Shrine (disambiguation)|ja|広峯神社 (曖昧さ回避)|lt=Hiromine Shrine|lt_ja=広峯神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hiromine Shrine (disambiguation)|qq=}}, {{ill|Yakumo Shrine|ja|八雲神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yakumo Shrine|qq=}}, {{ill|Suga Shrine|ja|須賀神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Suga Shrine|qq=}}, and {{ill|Susanoo Shrine|ja|素盞嗚神社|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Susanoo Shrine|qq=}}, names which vary according to the era and source.

Among the current enshrined deities, only a few shrines have {{ill|Gozu Tennō|ja|牛頭天王|1=Gozu Tennō|1=Gozu Tennō|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Gozu Tennō|13=User:Immanuelle/Gozu Tennō|qq=}} as their primary deity, while many shrines enshrine {{ill|Susanoo|1=Susanoo-no-Mikoto|ja|スサノオ|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Susanoo|13=User:Immanuelle/Susanoo-no-Mikoto|qq=}}, who had been syncretized with Gozu Tennō through {{ill|Shinbutsu Shūgō|ja|神仏習合|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinbutsu Shūgō|qq=}}. During the Meiji era's separation of Shinto and Buddhism ({{ill|Shinbutsu Bunri|ja|神仏分離|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinbutsu Bunri|qq=}}), some shrines reverted to the deities recorded in ancient tradition rather than enshrining Susanoo.

Since the Meiji era, due to joint enshrinement ({{ill|Joint Enshrinement|ja|合祀|1=co-Enshrinement|2=ja|3=合祀|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Joint Enshrinement|13=User:Immanuelle/co-Enshrinement|qq=}}) with other shrines and the renaming of institutions such as the Tsushima Gozu Tennō Shrine, many shrines have changed their names to, for example, Tsushima Shrine. Additionally, influenced by the separation of Shinto and Buddhism and such joint enshrinement, there are shrines where the enshrined deity is not {{ill|Gozu Tennō|ja|牛頭天王|1=Gozu Tennō|1=Gozu Tennō|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Gozu Tennō|13=User:Immanuelle/Gozu Tennō|qq=}}, and some where Gozu Tennō is interpreted as a deity other than Susanoo. In certain regions, the legacy of this phenomenon can even be seen in local place names bearing "Tennō."

